In [[mathematics]], '''Gauss<U+2013>Jordan elimination''' is a version of [[Gaussian elimination]] that puts zeros both above and below each [[pivot element]] as it goes from the top row of the given matrix to the bottom. In other words, Gauss-Jordan elimination brings a matrix to [[reduced row echelon form]], whereas Gaussian elimination takes it only as far as [[row echelon form]].
It is considerably less efficient than the two-stage Gaussian elimination algorithm.

== References ==
* Lipschutz, Seymour, and Lipson, Mark. "Schaum's Outlines: Linear Algebra". Tata McGraw-hill edition. Delhi 2001. pp. 69-80.

